th party link\n | winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n | loser = Republican Party (United States)\n | swing =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin\n | title=[[United States Senate election in Virginia, 2008]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2008/2008Stat.htm#stateVA | title=2008 Election Statistics | publisher=Clerk.house.gov | accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n | party = Democratic Party (United States)\n | candidate = Mark Warner\n | votes = 2,369,327\n | percentage = 65.03%\n | change = +65.03%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate = [[Jim Gilmore]]\n | votes = 1,228,830\n | percentage = 33.72%\n | change = -48.85%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party = Independent Greens of Virginia\n | candidate = Glenda Parker\n | votes = 21,690\n | percentage = 0.60%\n | change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n | candidate = [[Bill Redpath]]\n | votes = 20,269\n | percentage = 0.56%\n | change =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n | party = Write-ins\n | candidate =\n | votes = 3,178\n | percentage = 0.09%\n | change =\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n | votes = 1,140,497\n | percentage = 31.30%\n | change = -41.53%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n | votes = 3,643,294\n | percentage =\n | change =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n | winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n | loser = Republican Party (United States)\n | swing =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin\n | title=[[United States Senate election in Virginia, 2014]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://cms.sbe.virginia.gov/public/?p=election_summary&id=1&loc=true | title=November 4, 2014-General-Election Results Official Results | publisher=Virginia Department of Elections | accessdate=November 27, 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107151421/http://cms.sbe.virginia.gov/public/?p=election_summary&id=1&loc=true | archivedate=November 7, 2014 | df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n | party = Democratic Party (United States)\n | candidate = Mark Warner (Incumbent)\n | votes = 1,073,667\n | percentage = 49.15%\n | change = -15.88%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate = [[Ed Gillespie]]\n | votes = 1,055,940\n | percentage = 48.34%\n | change = +14.62%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n | party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n | candidate = [[Robert Sarvis]]\n | votes = 53,102\n | percentage = 2.43%\n | change = +1.87%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n | party = Other\n | candidate = Write-ins\n | votes = 1,764\n | percentage = 0.08%\n | change = -0.01%\n}}\n{{Election box plurality\n | votes = 17,727\n | percentage = 0.81%\n | change = -30.49%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n | votes = 2,184,473\n | percentage = \n | change = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n | winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n | swing =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nWarner is married to Lisa Collis, whom he had met in 1984 at a [[fraternity]] party in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=10Things/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2017}} While on their [[honeymoon]] in 1989 in [[Egypt]] and [[Greece]], Warner became ill; when he returned home, doctors discovered he had suffered a near-fatal [[Appendicitis|burst appendix]]. Warner spent two months in the hospital recovering from the illness.<ref name=10Things/>  During her husband's tenure as governor, Collis was the first Virginia [[first lady]] to use her birth name. Warner and Collis have three daughters: Madison, Gillian, and Eliza.\n\nWarner is involved in farming and winemaking at his Rappahannock Bend farm. There, he grows {{convert|15|acre|m2}} of [[grape]]s for [[Ingleside Vineyards]]; Ingleside bottles a [[private label]] that Warner offers at [[Charitable organization|charity]] auctions.<ref name=Farming>{{cite news|last=Bedard |first=Paul |title=A Modern-Day Thomas Jefferson? |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/articles/051128/28whisplead.htm |accessdate=March 19, 2012 |newspaper=U.S. News |date=November 20, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121215101/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/articles/051128/28whisplead.htm |archivedate=January 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWarner has an estimated net worth of $257 million as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pilotonline.com/news/government/politics/nation/report-mark-warner-nd-richest-member-of-congress/article_c36f185f-1256-5b36-8d51-359cd91d9151.html|title=Report: Mark Warner 2nd richest member of Congress|first=The|last=Virginian-Pilot|publisher=|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees==\nMark Warner has been awarded several [[honorary degrees]], these include:\n\n;Honorary degrees\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Virginia}} || '''2002''' || [[College of William and Mary]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/dont-check-out-warner-encourages-wm-grads-to-be-active-citizens.php|title='Don\u2019t check out': Warner encourages W&M grads to be active citizens|website=www.wm.edu|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|District of Columbia}} || '''2003''' || [[George Washington University]] || Doctor of Public 